he dramatic results of these 120 years of experimentation are consistent with his theory, as are observations in many other natural communities.The consumer-resource approach of this book is applicable to both animal and plant communities, but the majority of Professor Tilman's discussion concentrates on the structure of plant communities. All theoretical arguments are developed graphically, and formal mathematics is kept to a minimum. The final chapters of the book provide some testable speculations about resources and animal communities and explore such problems as the evolution of "super species," the differences between plant and animal community diversity patterns, and the cause of plant succession.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBiotic communities. 0aCompetition (Biology). 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh  aAgrostis.  aAlopecurus.  aArrhenatherum.  aChrysanthemum.  aCydotella.  aDaphnia.  aEnteromorpha.  aEscherichia coli.  aFestuca.  aFragilaria.  aLathyrus.  aMelosira.  aMicrocystis.  aNorth Dakota prairie.  aOscillatoria.  aPlantago.  aPoa.  aPseudomonas.  aRumex.  aScenedesmus.  aSkeletonema.  aStephanodiscus.  aSynedra.  aTabellaria.  ahumped diversity curve.  avascular plant diversity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691209654zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691209654423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691209654.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12ST